Well, for what it's worth, I just did it the same way that we handle the call to `super().__new__` (which will call `__init_subclass__` with the same kwargs) in line 109:

https://github.com/pydantic/pydantic/blob/0cd57b3e0c75d9622012de542e5ddc110fe55743/pydantic/main.py#L109

`__init_subclass__` will generally receives the keyword arguments that were passed in the class declaration:

```python
class MyClass:
    def __init_subclass__(cls, **kwargs):
        print(kwargs)

class MySubClass(MyClass, x=1):
    pass

#> {'x': 1}
```
which is why I wanted to pass them to `__pydantic_init_subclass__`.

I'm happy to add the other keyword arguments to the init_subclass call though; should we update the line 109 call too? (I think either way we probably should call with the same keyword arguments that the actual `__init_subclass__` receives.)

